<h1 class="c1"><a name="h.b7egspb6ick5"></a><span>Getting Started</span></h1>
<p class="c25 c1">&nbsp;</p>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.t3tg0axy5g5e"></a><span>Login</span></h2>
<h2 class="c21 c1 c15"><a name="h.4b29biuxbwt"></a><span>Direct URL - regular login screen</span></h2>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>The regular login screen is what you see when you write the direct URL for your Methvin installation.</span></p>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>[Login Pic]</span></p>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>You will be able to log into Methvin with either your email or your username. This way you can avoid having to remember yet-another-username.</span></p>
<h2 class="c21 c1 c15"><a name="h.4qicgeqbcbsx"></a><span>Recover a forgotten password</span></h2>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>If you forgot your password, click the “Forgot password?” link on the login screen. You will get a form that allows you to request a new password. Since e-mails are sent unencrypted you should change this temporary password immediately after the first login in your </span><span class="c0"><a class="c3" href="#id.9bvfu3n7t6x7">user account</a></span><span>.</span></p>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>[Forgot Username Pic]</span></p>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>PLEASE NOTE: You can only request a new password with an e-mail address that is already stored in an existing user account, and the new password will be sent to that address. If you get an error message you have probably been using Methvin with another e-mail address.</span></p>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>[Forgot Password Pic]</span></p>
<h2 class="c21 c1 c15"><a name="h.ee4ivuuflvmk"></a><span>Website-</span><span>Methvin</span><span>&nbsp;Single User login</span></h2>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>If your account is a Methvin Single User account, you will be automatically redirected to your Companys default pricing page.</span></p>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>If you have the Professional Addition, the site will provide you with the list of your available Companies.</span></p>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>If the system does not automatically log you in, or does not present you with the installation options, please contact Methvin Support Team, your Methvin account executive, or your organization Technical Support representative.</span></p>
<h2 class="c21 c1 c15"><a name="h.lno1o5adpqme"></a><span>Logout</span></h2>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>The logout link is located in the upper right corner of the screen next to the name of the logged-in user:</span></p>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>[Logout Pic]</span></p>
<h1 class="c1 c15"><a name="h.c8fjyxikdmvb"></a><span>Essential setup Steps</span></h1>
<h2 class="c1 c23"><a name="h.axmsovotkupx"></a><span>How to add your first Project, Suppliers, Subcontractors, Documents, etc.</span></h2>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>Depending on how you are using Methvin (and other things like your configuration, the edition you are using, etc) you will organize your information in some of the following “dimensions”:</span></p>
<ol class="c18" start="1">
<li class="c2 c1"><span>Projects</span></li>
<li class="c2 c1"><span>Pricing</span></li>
<li class="c1 c2"><span>Resources</span></li>
<li class="c2 c1"><span>Claims</span></li>
<li class="c2 c1"><span>Subcontractor adjudication</span></li>
<li class="c2 c1"><span>Suppliers</span></li>
<li class="c2 c1"><span>Subcontractors</span></li>
<li class="c2 c1"><span>Documents</span></li>
<li class="c2 c1"><span>Other (not covered in this section)</span></li>
</ol>
<p class="c1 c36"><span>Some of the above will give you access to what we call the “full add”, which is our short-name for the form that allows you to input all the detailed information</span></p>
<h1 class="c1"><a name="h.8cs5qhkmvmfc"></a><span>Import &amp; Export options</span></h1>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.7fra7gmvokev"></a><span>Import Client schedule</span></h2>
<h3 class="c12 c1"><a name="h.g0gmyc5a3y8"></a><span>Importing a client supplied schedule</span></h3>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>The best practice to insure a trouble free import of the Clients Schedule is by following this step by step procedure:</span></p>
<ol class="c18" start="1">
<li class="c2 c1"><span>First export an existing schedule, by clicking the Export to Excel Icon in the Pricing Module.</span></li>
<li class="c2 c1"><span>This will give you the excel import structure (i.e. Column header descriptions and sequence of columns) for your import.</span></li>
<li class="c2 c1"><span>Copy your new client supplied information to their appropriate column headers, then save the file.</span></li>
<li class="c2 c1"><span>Click on the Import Schedule icon to upload the clients schedule, Navigate to your newly created file and select it, then click the save button, this will import your client supplied schedule into the pricing module. </span></li>
</ol>
<p class="c1"><span>(pic)</span></p>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.g2mn5qjp7q6t"></a><span>Export Projects</span></h2>
<h3 class="c12 c1"><a name="h.csku9yci3i12"></a><span>Important information to remember when exporting a project</span></h3>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>When exporting a Project file, it is important to remembered that only the physical text data is saved, none of the uploaded files in the documents module are backed up to the file. When backing up your documents it is recommended you download them to your local computer. There is a “save” process within the system to allow you to zip save the entire documents content to your local drive.</span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>(pic)</span></p>
<h3 class="c12 c1"><a name="h.xg9gvvbe04wb"></a><span>Export a specific Project</span></h3>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>From the Projects window situated on the left hand side of the screen, right click on the Project you wish to download. This brings up the projects quick menu, select the Export Project menu item. This will save the project sql file to your computer. Important note, this does not save your uploaded files which were saved under the Documents Module. </span></p>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.d4jf35887cc"></a><span>Import Project</span></h2>
<h3 class="c12 c1"><a name="h.22k8dhsjgukq"></a><span>Import a specific Project sql file</span></h3>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>From the Projects window situated on the left hand side of the screen, add a new project to import your project into. From the righthand click import project menu navigate to the project file you wish to import, then click the save button, this will import your project.</span></p>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.x9nq7zzf3wub"></a><span>Duplicate Project</span></h2>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>From the projects right hand click menu select the Duplicate Project option, and by doing so it will make a copy of the selected project just below itself.</span></p>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.8ztavi6w3sp5"></a><span>Import Resource Schedule</span></h2>
<p class="c8 c1"><span>Following the following step by step procedure to import your resource schedule:</span></p>
<ol class="c18" start="5">
<li class="c2 c1"><span>Follow the Heading structure from the Resource Module, to insure the information is imported correctly. </span></li>
<li class="c2 c1"><span>Click on the Import Resource Schedule icon to upload your Resource Schedule, Navigate to your file and select it, then click the save button, this will import your Resource Schedul into the resource module.</span></li>
</ol>
<h1 class="c1"><a name="h.y389rc2kbzaa"></a><span>Pricing Module</span></h1>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.18jfim13w60c"></a><span>Basic Pricing</span></h2>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>Basic pricing is possible through inserting your required gross rate into pricing tabs gross rate column. This can then be printed as a client report. This saves automatically and you have successfully &nbsp;created your first price response in Methvin.</span></p>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.u2g57y37uchz"></a><span>Complex Worksheet Pricing</span></h2>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>Under each item in the schedule there is a worksheet dynamically attached. Here you can drag in resources or worksheets from the accordion menu on the right side of the pricing module, decreasing your pricing time and improving the accuracy of your tender.</span></p>
<h3 class="c1"><a name="h.y6m782lfya6x"></a><span>Pricing with Variables</span></h3>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>The complex worksheet allows you to set variables for pricing, for example the distance from a quarry to the site or the depth of a trench. When you set up a new project, with a similar item to price, &nbsp;all that is required is to adjust the variables to the new circumstances. </span></p>
<h3 class="c1"><a name="h.88dew969ofe2"></a><span>The Function column</span></h3>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>This facilitates the use of any mathematical function. Caution, &nbsp;watch the brackets when using complicated equations.</span></p>
<p class="c1 c12"><span class="c14">[Pic]</span></p>
<h3 class="c12 c1"><a name="h.f3ws1k74r5j9"></a><span>Java Functions</span></h3>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>Unique to Methvin, you are able to utilise any </span><span class="c0"><a class="c3" href="http://www.w3schools.com/jsref/jsref_obj_math.asp">function available in Java</a></span><span>&nbsp;to automate your complex pricing. </span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>Examples:</span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>if ([</span><span class="c14">“your variable”</span><span>2]&gt;5) {yes} else {no} - Returns no </span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>Math.round(2.5) - Returns 3</span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>var x = Math.PI - Returns PI</span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>var y = Math.sqrt(16) - Returns the square root of 16</span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span class="c14">[Pic]</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c35">Sub-schedules</span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>When the client provides one item for a complex section of work, &nbsp;for example, a Lump Sum Item calls for the construction of a bridge. If you change the item into a sub-schedule item by clicking on the icon at the top of the Pricing Module, any items pertaining to the sub-section item will roll up the clients item when printing out this report. Under the sub-schedule you are able to add as much detail as you require, to allow you to price the item accurately. The Client report will reflect only the Lump sum as dictated by the sub- schedule, in this case “Bridge”.</span></p>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.gyd1465etcow"></a><span>Copying Pricing</span></h2>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>There are two ways in which you can speed up your pricing by copying detailed pricing from previously priced projects:</span></p>
<ol class="c24" start="1">
<li class="c1 c20 c28"><span>Select the principle project from the dropdown box at the top of the Pricing Module</span></li>
<li class="c28 c1 c20"><span>Import an item and its detailed pricing from any project into your schedule. This is done by dragging and dropping from the righthand side accordions menu ‘Copy Item &amp; Pricing’ the item across to your schedule.</span></li>
</ol>
<p class="c1"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;OR</span></p>
<ol class="c24" start="1">
<li class="c28 c1 c20"><span>Copy the detailed pricing from a previous project by going to the right hand side accordions menu ‘Copy Pricing’ drag an item down to the detailed pricing tab at the bottom of the Pricing Module.</span></li>
</ol>
<h1 class="c1"><a name="h.xmhpbvk6m3wo"></a><span>Resource Module</span></h1>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.mma8lw77pmny"></a><span>Basic Resource Pricing</span></h2>
<p class="c1"><span>Base rates: &nbsp;T</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span>he rate is inserted directly into the resource item line.</span></p>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.l2f9bzca43gl"></a><span>Complex Resource Pricing</span></h2>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>Under each resource</span><span>&nbsp;there is a worksheet dynamically attached. Here you can drag in resources or worksheets from the accordion menu on the right side of the pricing module, decreasing your pricing time and improving the accuracy of your tender.</span></p>
<h3 class="c1"><a name="h.aqrhsjmx1xsg"></a><span>Pricing with Variables</span></h3>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>The complex worksheet allows you to set variables for pricing, for example the distance from a quarry to the site or the depth of a trench. When you set up a new project, with a similar item to price, &nbsp;all that is required is to adjust the variables to the new circumstances. </span></p>
<h3 class="c1"><a name="h.1y1yvw2idtks"></a><span>The Function column</span></h3>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>This facilitates the use of any mathematical function. Caution, &nbsp;watch the brackets when using complicated equations.</span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span class="c14">[Pic]</span></p>
<h3 class="c12 c1"><a name="h.hj3yfz58ak9z"></a><span>Java Functions</span></h3>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>Unique to Methvin, you are able to utilise any </span><span class="c0"><a class="c3" href="http://www.w3schools.com/jsref/jsref_obj_math.asp">function available in Java</a></span><span>&nbsp;to automate your complex pricing. </span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>Examples:</span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>if ([</span><span class="c14">“your variable”</span><span>2]&gt;5) {yes} else {no} - Returns no </span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>Math.round(2.5) - Returns 3</span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>var x = Math.PI - Returns PI</span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>var y = Math.sqrt(16) - Returns the square root of 16</span></p>
<p class="c12 c1"><span class="c14">[Pic]</span></p>
<h1 class="c1"><a name="h.pug4sbog4625"></a><span>Tender Evaluation</span></h1>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.ijdionm3si5o"></a><span>Lock Selling Rates</span></h2>
<p class="c1 c23"><span>This is a powerful tool, whereby each gross/selling rate can be individually locked to the required value by checking the checkbox “Lock?” found in the ‘Pricing Module’.</span></p>
<p class="c1 c23"><span>Once you are satisfied with your tender price it is possible to lock all the gross rates by selecting the checkbox icon in the pricing module menu.</span></p>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.3vziv3i4224x"></a><span>Imbalanced Rates</span></h2>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>Once you have accurately priced up an item and come up with its cost rate the item is automatically marked up by the default markup as set in the Pricing Module. If for any reason you believe the item to be over or under scheduled, it is very easy to adjust its markup by either inputting the required Gross Rate or inputting the required percentage markup. This then automatically locks in the new markup by setting the lock gross rate checkbox to “true”.</span></p>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.1gbtbus8d6iw"></a><span>Markup - % for the Entire Project</span></h2>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>In the top right hand side of the screen under the Pricing Module it is possible to select the percentage that you would like to mark up the entire project. Once you have selected the required markup, click on the “Calculate” button at the top of the screen, this will adjust the percentage markup for the entire project to your revised markup percentage. If any items have been locked to allow for imbalanced items rates, they will be ignored and their previous markup will remain.</span></p>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.2l3vlfut66cm"></a><span>Markup - Individual Items</span></h2>
<p class="c12 c1"><span>For example if you wish to markup a section of the schedule by 3% and the rest of the project by 8.5% it is possible to set the global percentage markup as described before to 3% then click the calculate button. Individually set the ‘Lock?’ button to true for the section of the schedule you wish to mark up by 3%. Change the global percentage markup to 8.5% and click the calculate button once more, this will then markup the remainder of the scheduled items which don't have there checkboxes selected up the required 8.5%.</span></p>
<h2 class="c1"><a name="h.lxu0z2wzirrg"></a><span>Cost Codes</span></h2>
<p class="c1"><span>Methvin allows you to define your tender with cost codes</span></p>
<h1 class="c1"><a name="h.2u14tcapgg22"></a><span>Claims module</span></h1>
